description.narrative: Community-level institutions improve the use of safe water, hand washing with soap and use of latrines by children and families though promotion of good hygiene practices and meeting of WASH infrastructure standards., which contributes to Sanitation, Wash And Emergencies, Wash In Schools And Ecd Centres. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By the end of 2020, households and communities have access to safe drinking water, sanitation, and healthy environments and good hygiene practices are equitably improved in target regions

description.narrative: In 2019, 630 schools and 121 health centres were certified one Star and promote behaviour change and create demand. This represents 13% out of all schools and 14% out of all health centres in the targeted 10 regions. 11 schools and 20 health centres received 3 Star certification for having reached basic WASH services and meeting national standards. Menstrual Hygiene Management activities were integrated into the curricula of 1,367 schools, and 226 out of 1,000 planned schools have implemented MHM activities. In total almost 130,000 children including 63,000 girls benefited from UNICEF WASH program in Institutions. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:31/12/2019
